---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Prose from '../components/Prose.astro';
import PostCard from '../components/PostCard.astro';

export const prerender = true;

const variants = [
  {
    id: 'v-current',
    label: 'Current',
    blurb: 'Baseline — body 15–16px, column 680px.',
  },
  {
    id: 'v-a-prose',
    label: 'A · prose only',
    blurb: 'Body bumps to 17–18.5px, column 740px, leading 1.7. Chrome unchanged.',
  },
  {
    id: 'v-b-prose',
    label: 'B · prose only',
    blurb: 'Body bumps to 18–20px, column 780px, lighter heading weights. Chrome unchanged.',
  },
  {
    id: 'v-a-site',
    label: 'A · site-wide',
    blurb: 'Same A bumps, but `--text-base` and `--content-width` change globally — nav, cards, footer scale too.',
  },
  {
    id: 'v-b-site',
    label: 'B · site-wide',
    blurb: 'Same B bumps applied globally.',
  },
];

const samplePosts = [
  {
    title: 'AI That Actually Works',
    date: new Date('2026-04-26'),
    description:
      'The workflows that feel magical share three ingredients: a clear plan, the right context, and a way to validate.',
    tags: ['ai', 'work'],
    href: '#',
  },
  {
    title: 'The Great Collectors',
    date: new Date('2025-11-12'),
    description:
      'On the people who quietly compound taste over decades — and what their shelves teach us about attention.',
    tags: ['essays', 'taste'],
    href: '#',
  },
  {
    title: 'Sharp Tools and Interesting Problems',
    date: new Date('2025-09-04'),
    description: 'A short defense of investing in your tools before you need them.',
    tags: ['craft'],
    href: '#',
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout title="Typography Preview" description="A/B compare typography variants">
  <div class="picker-wrap">
    <div class="picker">
      <div class="picker__title">Typography variant</div>
      <div class="picker__options" role="radiogroup" aria-label="Typography variant">
        {variants.map((v, i) => (
          <label class="picker__option">
            <input
              type="radio"
              name="variant"
              value={v.id}
              checked={i === 0}
              data-variant={v.id}
            />
            <span class="picker__label">{v.label}</span>
          </label>
        ))}
      </div>
      <p class="picker__blurb" data-blurb>{variants[0].blurb}</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <article class="post">
    <header class="post__header">
      <time datetime="2026-04-26T00:00:00.000Z">April 26, 2026</time>
      <h1>AI That Actually Works</h1>
      <p class="post__description">
        The workflows that feel magical share three ingredients: a clear plan,
        the right context, and a way to validate.
      </p>
      <div class="post__tags">
        <span class="tag">ai</span>
        <span class="tag">work</span>
      </div>
    </header>

    <Prose>
      <p>
        The bulk of the conversation about AI agents in 2026 is happening inside
        the software world. Coding assistants, autonomous developers, agentic
        IDEs. That's where the loudest experimentation is happening. But the
        fundamentals that make those workflows feel magical aren't really about
        code. They apply just as cleanly to a customer support team, a marketing
        operation, a finance back office, or any other corner of a business
        trying to get real leverage out of AI.
      </p>
      <p>
        After spending a lot of time both building with these tools and helping
        teams figure out how to adopt them, I keep coming back to the same
        observation. The workflows that feel genuinely magical (and the ones
        where AI produces something close to what you'd produce yourself) share
        three ingredients:
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>A clear plan</strong>: detailed enough that "done" is obvious</li>
        <li><strong>The right context</strong>: access to the data, docs, and history so it's not guessing</li>
        <li><strong>A way to validate</strong>: a feedback loop so it can check its own work</li>
      </ol>
      <p>
        When all three are present, agents stop feeling like a novelty and start
        feeling like a teammate. When even one is missing, you get the
        experience most people have had with AI: a confident-sounding answer
        that misses the mark, needs heavy rework, or hallucinates its way into
        the wrong outcome.
      </p>

      <h2>1. A clear plan</h2>
      <p>
        The biggest mistake I see is treating AI like a wish-granting genie. You
        toss it a vague prompt, hope it dreams up the right thing, and then feel
        disappointed when it doesn't. Vague directions leave enormous room for
        the model to either hallucinate or do something perfectly competent
        that's just pointed in the wrong direction.
      </p>
      <p>
        The mental shift that unlocks better results is this: spend the bulk of
        your time on the task in the planning phase. Work back and forth with
        the AI to construct a detailed plan, then review and refine it. The
        more effort you put in here, the less effort you'll spend cleaning up
        the output later. This is probably the single biggest unlock for people
        who feel like AI isn't working for them. For a longer take on the same
        idea, see <a href="#">the planning-first essay</a>.
      </p>
      <blockquote>
        The other thing a great plan does is explicitly describe the ideal
        outcome. Not just the steps, but what "done" looks like. If you only
        specify how the work should be done, the agent has no real way to know
        whether what it produced is actually right.
      </blockquote>

      <h2>2. The right context</h2>
      <p>
        If the agent is guessing about how it interacts with the rest of your
        world, it has to take creative liberties. Those liberties are where
        hallucinations come from. Context is what shrinks that gap. Depending on
        the work, it might mean:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Details about the customers the agent is working with</li>
        <li>Documentation for your product</li>
        <li>Your help desk wiki and internal knowledge base</li>
        <li>A customer's account history: what plan they're on, how long they've been a member, their most recent service interaction</li>
        <li>Brand guidelines, tone of voice, prior examples of work you considered "good"</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        The more relevant context the agent has, the closer its output gets to
        what you or a senior person on your team would have produced. Context
        doesn't just reduce hallucinations. It raises the ceiling on what the
        agent can actually do.
      </p>

      <h3>An aside on tooling</h3>
      <p>
        An agent with the right context can make judgment calls that look
        informed rather than generic. Even small things — like access to the
        last <code>git log</code> entry or the customer's most recent ticket —
        change the texture of what comes back.
      </p>

      <h2>Why this matters</h2>
      <p>
        When all three ingredients are in place, hallucinations drop and quality
        climbs. When people tell me they've tried AI and aren't getting great
        results, it almost always comes back to one or more of these three
        pieces being missing. The agent isn't underperforming because the
        technology is bad. It's underperforming because it's been set up to
        fail.
      </p>
      <p>
        Plan deeply. Provide context generously. Build in validation. That's the
        recipe.
      </p>
    </Prose>
  </article>

  <section class="chrome-sample">
    <div class="section-heading">
      <h2>How chrome looks at this size</h2>
      <a href="#">view all →</a>
    </div>
    <div class="chrome-sample__cards">
      {samplePosts.map((p) => (
        <PostCard
          title={p.title}
          date={p.date}
          description={p.description}
          tags={p.tags}
          href={p.href}
        />
      ))}
    </div>
  </section>

  <script is:inline define:vars={{ variants }}>
    const root = document.documentElement;
    const radios = document.querySelectorAll('input[name="variant"]');
    const blurb = document.querySelector('[data-blurb]');
    const ids = variants.map((v) => v.id);

    function apply(id) {
      ids.forEach((x) => root.classList.remove(x));
      root.classList.add(id);
      const v = variants.find((x) => x.id === id);
      if (v && blurb) blurb.textContent = v.blurb;
    }

    radios.forEach((r) =>
      r.addEventListener('change', (e) => apply(e.target.value))
    );

    apply('v-current');
  </script>
</BaseLayout>

<style is:global>
  /* =========================================================
     Variant overrides
     ========================================================= */

  /* --- A · prose only --- */
  :root.v-a-prose .post {
    max-width: 740px;
    margin-inline: auto;
  }
  :root.v-a-prose .prose,
  :root.v-a-prose .post__description {
    font-size: clamp(1.0625rem, 1rem + 0.3vw, 1.15rem);
    line-height: 1.7;
  }
  :root.v-a-prose .prose p,
  :root.v-a-prose .prose li {
    font-size: inherit;
  }
  :root.v-a-prose .post__description {
    font-size: clamp(1.25rem, 1.15rem + 0.5vw, 1.4rem);
    font-style: italic;
  }
  :root.v-a-prose .post h1 {
    font-weight: 600;
  }
  :root.v-a-prose .prose h2 { font-weight: 500; }
  :root.v-a-prose .prose h3 { font-weight: 500; }

  /* --- B · prose only (Maggie-faithful) --- */
  :root.v-b-prose .post {
    max-width: 780px;
    margin-inline: auto;
  }
  :root.v-b-prose .prose,
  :root.v-b-prose .post__description {
    font-size: clamp(1.125rem, 1.05rem + 0.4vw, 1.25rem);
    line-height: 1.7;
  }
  :root.v-b-prose .prose p,
  :root.v-b-prose .prose li {
    font-size: inherit;
  }
  :root.v-b-prose .post__description {
    font-size: clamp(1.375rem, 1.25rem + 0.6vw, 1.5rem);
    font-style: italic;
    line-height: 1.5;
  }
  :root.v-b-prose .post h1 {
    font-size: clamp(2.5rem, 2rem + 1.8vw, 3.75rem);
    font-weight: 500;
    letter-spacing: -0.025em;
  }
  :root.v-b-prose .prose h2 {
    font-size: clamp(1.625rem, 1.4rem + 0.8vw, 2.125rem);
    font-weight: 500;
  }
  :root.v-b-prose .prose h3 { font-weight: 500; }

  /* --- A · site-wide --- */
  :root.v-a-site {
    --text-base: clamp(1.0625rem, 1rem + 0.3vw, 1.15rem);
    --content-width: 740px;
  }
  :root.v-a-site .prose,
  :root.v-a-site .post__description {
    line-height: 1.7;
  }
  :root.v-a-site .post__description {
    font-size: clamp(1.25rem, 1.15rem + 0.5vw, 1.4rem);
    font-style: italic;
  }
  :root.v-a-site .post h1 { font-weight: 600; }
  :root.v-a-site .prose h2,
  :root.v-a-site .prose h3 { font-weight: 500; }

  /* --- B · site-wide --- */
  :root.v-b-site {
    --text-base: clamp(1.125rem, 1.05rem + 0.4vw, 1.25rem);
    --content-width: 780px;
  }
  :root.v-b-site .prose,
  :root.v-b-site .post__description {
    line-height: 1.7;
  }
  :root.v-b-site .post__description {
    font-size: clamp(1.375rem, 1.25rem + 0.6vw, 1.5rem);
    font-style: italic;
    line-height: 1.5;
  }
  :root.v-b-site .post h1 {
    font-size: clamp(2.5rem, 2rem + 1.8vw, 3.75rem);
    font-weight: 500;
    letter-spacing: -0.025em;
  }
  :root.v-b-site .prose h2 {
    font-size: clamp(1.625rem, 1.4rem + 0.8vw, 2.125rem);
    font-weight: 500;
  }
  :root.v-b-site .prose h3 { font-weight: 500; }
</style>

<style>
  /* =========================================================
     Picker (sticky control bar)
     ========================================================= */
  .picker-wrap {
    position: sticky;
    top: var(--nav-height);
    z-index: 50;
    margin: calc(-1 * var(--space-10)) calc(-1 * var(--space-6)) var(--space-8);
    padding: var(--space-4) var(--space-6);
    background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--color-bg-raised) 92%, transparent);
    backdrop-filter: blur(10px);
    -webkit-backdrop-filter: blur(10px);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .picker {
    max-width: var(--wide-width);
    margin: 0 auto;
  }

  .picker__title {
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    font-weight: 700;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
  }

  .picker__options {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: var(--space-2);
  }

  .picker__option {
    cursor: pointer;
  }

  .picker__option input {
    position: absolute;
    opacity: 0;
    pointer-events: none;
  }

  .picker__label {
    display: inline-block;
    padding: var(--space-2) var(--space-4);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: 100px;
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    font-weight: 500;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    background: var(--color-bg);
    transition:
      background var(--transition-fast),
      color var(--transition-fast),
      border-color var(--transition-fast);
  }

  .picker__option:hover .picker__label {
    color: var(--color-text-heading);
    border-color: var(--color-text-muted);
  }

  .picker__option input:checked + .picker__label {
    background: var(--color-accent);
    color: white;
    border-color: var(--color-accent);
  }

  .picker__blurb {
    margin-top: var(--space-3);
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    font-style: italic;
    max-width: 70ch;
  }

  /* =========================================================
     Post (mirrors writing/[slug].astro)
     ========================================================= */
  .post {
    transition: max-width var(--transition-base);
  }

  .post__header {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-8);
  }

  .post__header time {
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
  }

  .post__header h1 {
    font-size: var(--text-4xl);
    margin-top: var(--space-2);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
    transition:
      font-size var(--transition-base),
      font-weight var(--transition-base);
  }

  .post__description {
    font-size: var(--text-lg);
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
    transition:
      font-size var(--transition-base),
      line-height var(--transition-base);
  }

  .post__tags {
    display: flex;
    gap: var(--space-2);
    flex-wrap: wrap;
  }

  /* =========================================================
     Chrome sample
     ========================================================= */
  .chrome-sample {
    margin-top: var(--space-16);
    padding-top: var(--space-8);
    border-top: 1px solid var(--color-border-subtle);
  }

  .chrome-sample__cards {
    margin-top: var(--space-4);
  }
</style>
